    "body": "### Problem\n\n### Description: \nIf you run a batch script via the `jobstart()` function, and within the batch script it has output to `CON`, then that output will be printed directly into the current buffer at the cursor position. \n\n### Images:\n\n1. <img width=\"571\" height=\"410\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/04b4e28e-1a1c-42f8-b47f-104768ff1c5a\" />\n\n2. <img width=\"571\" height=\"410\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/2de240c1-906c-464d-b32d-a52cff23a273\" />\n\n3. <img width=\"571\" height=\"410\" alt=\"Image\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/81cc6d7c-be10-4e38-a2c6-51d28198dc94\" />\n\n### Extra background: \nI use the gutentags plugin, which uses a batch script to auto-update update tag files in the background. That script outputs its log info to CON by default, so with Nvim 0.12+ (bug seems to have started with the new UI stuff), it became unusable until I tracked down exactly what was causing it. Thankfully a pretty simple temporary fix (for anyone using Nvim 0.12+ with gutentags on windows in the terminal) is to modify the gutentags script to output to NUL instead of CON.\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n1. Make a simple batch script like so (bug still occurs with or without `@echo off`):\n```\necho FOOBARBAZFOOBARBAZFOOBARBAZ > CON\n```\n2. Go to the directory of the batch script (let's say named `test.bat`), and then run `:call jobstart('test.bat')`. You should then see the output of `FOOBARBAZFOOBARBAZFOOBARBAZ` written at your cursor position. It won't go away unless the screen is refreshed, like by `ctrl-l`.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nIn vim, and versions of neovim pre 0.12, the output goes nowhere visible. The expected behavior is that it acts as if there was no output.\n\nAt the very least, the output should go into the messages log or something, but imo it should just stay unseen as it was before. \n\n### Nvim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.13.0-dev-601+gd214c24129\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno, vim 9.0\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWindows 11\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nPowershell\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nnone\n\n### Installation\n\nbuild from repo",
